{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_dean_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583000/1920111501/0314.xml":{"full_text":"Daily Financial Gossip\ntty HOLLAND\nNew York, November 14.\u2014(Special.)\nJ. P. Morgan and company offered a\ni'cw days ago for sale the balance of\nthe 7 per cent preferred stock of the\nstandard Oil company of New Jersey,\nthis balance representing the amount of\nstock in the hands of the syndicate over\nand above that which was subscribed for.\nProbably this offering was nothing more\nthan a formality. This balance which\nin the aggregate was for a large amount\nwps speedily cold and the syndicate\nwhich underwrote the offering of the\nstandard Oil company was dissolved.\nThis might be considered an unim\nportant, almost purely local financial\nmcidenL Hut it may be taken as a text\nupon which may be based considerations\nwhich will be of value to business, offer\ning encouragement in these days which\nare characterized by some business de\npression.\nIt is a conspicuous example of the fact\nhat while retail and wholesale business\nand manufacturing plants are now pass\ning through a period of more or less de\npression, nevertheless fundamentally the\nconditions are healthful and justify the\nbelief that this business depression is\nto be but brief. For within a few days\nmany very large financial transactions\nin addition to the one with which J. P.\n.Morgan was identified as syndicate leader\nhave been perfected These transactions\nare not confined to New York City.\n,7'rom Chicago comes announcement that\nfinancial syndicates in that city under\nwrote last week twenty millions of the\nnotes of a leather corporaton and an\n1 ther syndicate underwrote some ten mil\nlions of the &otea of the Kansas City\nPower and Light company.\nSo also in New York a syndicate which\nunderwrote an issue of four million five\nhundred thousand of ten years, 7 per\ncent go.d debentures issued by one of\nthe largest oil companies was gratified\nby the immediate heavy over subscrip\ntion which followed the offering of these\nIF THERE W ERE\nDANGER OF PANIC\n7f there were any clanger of panic or\nof such business depression as would be\nfollowed by bankruptcies in all pans of\nthe country, it would not be possible to\nreport tha.t the financiers and the syndi\ncate not only undertook to market many\nissues of bonds and notes, but also to\nreport that these offerings were over\nsubscribed almost as soon as they were\n?i}ade.\nFurthermore, r would be useless at\nthis time to organize a foreign trade\nfinancing corporation with a capital of\na hundred mhlio.iu less unless funda\nmental conditions were sound and unless\nit was made evident that by financial aid\nof this kind our international trade will\nbe maintained or increased. Then again\nsomething like a hundred and sixty mil\nlions In credits anil loans have beer, j\nmade by banks and individuals in tha 1\nUnited States recently to foreign nations\nand municipalities. AM most all of these I\nare Kuropean nations. The Scandinavian j\npeninsula received forty-five millions.\nDenmark twenty-five millions, Copen\nhagen fifteen millions, Switzerland fifty- 1\nfive millions and two cities of Switzer\nland. Zurich and Berne, twelve millions\nin all\nIf there were to be overwhelming\nbusiness depression or if there were don\ngror that credit would be strained to\nthe breaking point, transactions of this\nkind would have been impossible.\nXHE CREDIT PEAK\nAlmost without exception those who\n\u2022are competent to judge say that thf\nstrain upon credit, much of which was\ndue to the. call for financing the move\nment of the greatest crops in the ag\ngregate over harvested in the United\nStates, ia ending if it has not already\nended. Kor ft is commonly reported in\nthe financial district that the peak of\nthe demand for credit, especially for\nmoving crops and other purposes, has\nbeen passed. We should begin to feel\nlater in the autumn or early in the\nwinter the influence of the inflow of\nfunds due to the marketing of the\ncrops.\nANOTHER MELON\nElbridge G. Snow as president of prob\nably the largest fire insurance company\n*be United tSates, has again demon*\nt*ratod hid wsitraordinary ability ftvr\nskillful managing of a business of this\nkind. For it Is probably due to his\nadvice that the directors of the Home\nInsurance company now recommended to\nthe shareholders that the capital stock\nbe increased from six millions to twelve\nmillions. The new shares are to be of*\nfered stockholders of record at $1S0.\na share. In this way $3,000,000 will be\nadded to the already large surplus of\nthe company.\nAs the shares of this company have\nbeen quoted at about $570. the increase\nof stock for which shareholders will j\npay $150 a share means that a melon is\nto he Sliced, each slice representing $200\nprofit. But the cutting of a melon in\nthese days has not the same value whien\nwent with a transaction of that kind\nbefore our war taxes were enacted. To\nday the rutting of a melon means ad\nding a considerable amount on negotia\nble paper to a shareholder's supply, but\nIt also means that the shareholder will\nnot be disposed to sell the new shares'\nbecause if he does the strong arm of\nthe government tax collector will bo ex\ntended so as to grasp a very large per\ncentage of the profits.\nThe relation between labor and capital\nhas been a subject to which President\nSnow has given earnest consideration.\nHe believes that employes are entitled\nto a larger share of the corporations by\nwhich they are employed than most of\nthem receive, believing that if the em\nployes were In this way recognized much\nof the friction between capital and labor\nwould be ended. At his suggestion the\ndirectors of the corrtjrany of which he\nis president decided to adopt a nev\npolicy. It is not _called profit-sharing,\nbut by another name. It is spoken of\nas dividend paying, for this company\nnow sets apart from its net profits r\u00ab\nper cent which are to be paid to the\nemployes upon a graduated scale. This\nwill be in addition to their salaries or\ncommissions. The other 50 per cent is\npaid to the stockholders in the form of\ndividends. President Snow calls this a\ndividend paying policy and not a profit\nsharing one. although in principle the\ntwo methods ore similar.\nWeekly Cotton Review\nBy Asbind feted Pm\u00ab\nNerrt York, November 14.\u2014While thei*3\nwere substantial advances in the price\nof cotton in the early sessions of las\nweek, the trend was strongly lower la\nter and on the closing session prices ot\nmost months in the contract department\nwere at new low levels for the season.\nDecember dropped to it.21c and Ma\\\nto 16.88c. At the highest the market was\n50 to 8S points above the level of the\nclose of tho preceding week and at the\nlowest it was i'2 to J.W points under. Tin\nrange was 142 to 1?S' pohes and th m i\nresults of the week were losses of 77 iu\n97 points. December cl at 17.41.\nwhich, compared with IS.50c as the cloy\ning price on middling in the spot market\nIn the net results middling lost 1,.\npoints.\nThe selling -of the week was due main\nly to the constant flow of pessimisti'.\ntalk from other markets to unsatisfac\ntory world lliumclal Conditions, the clos\ning down or going on short time of many\ncotton mills, and the lower trend of\nprices of ilnished goods. On the closing\nsession the market was unfavorably af\nfected by the census bureau report on\nAmerican mills for October, which placed\nconsumption at 399,837 bales, against 457.\n\\A1 in September, and 5G<V>41 in October\nof last year. Upturns of the week were\nmainly due to covering of the short in\nterest. Unfavorable weather, too, at\ntimes, was hardly more than a steadying\ninfluence, although it was generally ac\nknowledged that bad weather had worked\nfurther serious injury to the grade of\ncotton open in the lields. The freezing\nweather over the belt at the end of\nthe week was regarded as definitely\nmarking the close of the season.\nThis week it is likely that a little more\nattention will be paid to the technical\nposition the market is drifting into as the\nresult of the long continued and heavy\nselling for short account and the great\nvolume of liquidation on the long side.\nReports from the Interior regarding the\neffect of weather conditions on cotton\nstill left in the Held will lie watched\nclosely and evidence of abandonment oi\nrieids would probably cause nervousness\namong aborts. Improvement in general\ntrade conditions would probably be tin*\nmost powerful bull influence that could\ndevelop while further slowing down in\nbusiness would encourage further sell\ning of contracts.\nAny increase in the spot demand would\n\u00bbe reflected immediately in a higher\nrange of contract values, but contracts\nwould also respond quickly to any easi\nness in the spot department.\nMany week-end trade circulars predict\nvrhat is known as a trading market for\nthe near future.\nSYN 0 CTCO N VENES TUESDAY\nMobile, November 34.\u2014(SpeftiaL)\u2014One\nof the most important matters that will\ndome before tho Presbyterian Synod cl\nAlabama, which will be in session here,\nbeginning Monday, at the Government\nStreet church, is the consideration of the\nsynod's part in what is known as the\n\"United Programme for Christian Kduca\ntlon of the f*resbytcriar. Church, U. 3.,\nfor the Mississippi Valley,\u201d including the\nstates of Alabama. Mississippi, Louisi\nana and Tennessee.\nThe feature of this programme, so tar\nas Alabama is concerned, is the part\nthat Alabama will take in raising funds\nfor the proposed Southwestern college to\nbe established at Memphis and the rais\ning of a sufficient sum to take care of\nthe Preebyterian College for Men at An\nniston, an important school that is un\nder the care of the synod.\nMONEY\nTO LOAN\nWe b#w Ktvt at our\ndisposal funds to loan\non Birmingham buai\nness and residential\nproperty. Reasonable\nrotes with prompt mtt\nINQUIRIES INVITED\nMarx