00abT>\nGO 65\n97 IW\n75 80\n90 100\nino no\n90 W\n100 106\n92 9o\n74 77\nNASEN S DASH\nFamous Explorer Working for Re\npatriation of Prisoners of War'\nBy FI WrCHER ALLEN\nLondon, November 1.\u2014(Reciprocal\nSTews Service.)\u2014Dr. Fridtjof Nansen\nworking under terrific pressure on his\ntask of repatriating: the remaining hail\nmillion prisoners of war. Two years\nlave elapsed since the armistice brought\na, cessation of hostilities, and yet\nthroughout Europe there are 506,000 sol\niiers who have been held, if not in ac\ntual captivity, at least in unwilling ex\n,le. Dr. Nansen has undertaken jtbe\nwork of restoring them to their homes,\nind the League of Nations has accepted\nthe responsibility of raising the neces\nsary funds and transportation.\nWinter, a black and dangerous winter\nor Europe, is coming on rapidly. There\ns already a severe coal shortage. Unrest\nind distress in Europe, with stalking\n'amine and hurrying frost, bring com\nilications Impossible of comprehension by\nhose away from the spot.\nDr. Nansen, who appreciates the Im\npending disaster perhaps more thorough\ny than most people, ns a harassed man\nLt present, and is convinced that unles*\nivery nation bends earnestly to its own\n:hare of the great task, thousands of\nnen who have endured suffering pass\nng human understanding during the last\new years will die during the winter. To\ntee the prisoners now being repatriated\ns to feel the force of Dr. Nansen's ap\n\u25barehenslon. They come out of their Ion;?:\nmprisonment lacking almost the abso\nute essentials of covering\u2014it can hardly\n>e called clothing\u2014and emaciated for\nrant of nourishment. Their physical\nondition is often very desperate. Ty\n>hus and other scourges are raging in\nhe countries of exile, and every day or\nletentlon is spent in the companionship of\nleath.\nThe funds subscribed by the various\nrovemments and paid in to the fund or\nhe League of Nations, guaranteed\n:ontlnuance of the work of repatriation\no the present, and by skillful manage\nment the cost has been kept down to the\nninimum figure.\nA fleet of ships has been chartered by\nhe league, mostly between Germany and\ntussia in the Baltic, but some are run\nting the six weeks trip between Ham\n>urg and Vladivostok. In the details ot\nhis operation, the League of Nations is\n\u25a0eceiving the co-operation of the Inter\ntational Red Cross and the German gov\nernment authorities. Cargoes are being\nI booked to keep down expenses, and art\nto negotiate with the soviet, nearsoviet,\ners. In early May there were over 200,\n1000 Russian prisoners in Germany, and\na similar number of central European\nprisoners in Russia, Siberia and Turkes\ntan. These were mostly Hungarians,\nAustrians-. Czechs, Rumanians, Poles and\nSerbs, and their condition in soviet Rus\nsia was pitiable in the extreme. Such\neffort was made, however, in their in\nterests, that the process of repatriation\nwent ahead at the rate of between 16,000\nand 2C.0C0 per week.\nThe League of Nations naturally was\nhampered greatly by the condition of the\ngovernment in various countries, having\nto negotiate with the soviet, near- siviet,\nex-enemy and disorganized states; and\n1 not infrequently the very absence of\nI government made the work practically\nimpossible.\nThe work is not finished. The winter\npresses on, and the routes will soon be\nclosed. Dr. Nansen begins to be anxious\nagain, feeling that though there are im\nmense difficulties in the way of obtain\ning the necessary shipping and funds, j\nand in the diplomatic negotiations witn j\n'ratijfltory governments, it is the simple-J\ndebt of the world, but a tremendous ob-\nligation by reason of ihs simplicity, to j\nthese 500,000 prisoners, suffering under j\nterrible circumstances, to return them to\ntheir homes and to a chance at least\nof life again in better surroundings. j\nMETALS IN SHIPBUILDING j\nEngines With Smaller Proportions of j\nIron and Steel Give Best Results j\n\nI London, November 1,\u2014(Reciprocal j\nNews Service.)\u2014A significant hint was\nthrown out by the chairman of the tn-\nstitute of Metals at this year's conven- j\ntion of that body. He pointed out that j\nwhile the internal combustion engines I\nused to drive merchant ships contained\nonly 3 per cent of metals other than steel, j\nthe driving equipment of the latest Brit-.\nish submarines (oi! engines, steam tu.r- j\nbines and electrical machinery com\nbined), showed a proportion as high as J\n37 per cent. Therefore, the marine an-\ngineer would find in naval practice sue*\ngestions for increasing power and re-\nducing weight by using some of the won-\nderfully strong, yet light alloys whicn j\nBritish metallurgists had developed. j\nCAMPBELL ORCUTT\nCOTTON BROKERS\nSuite 217-218 Wocdward Bldg\nLocal Phone Main 3141.\nLong Distance 9Pt>5.\nFast. Daect Private Wire*\nCon \u2022spcndence Solicited.\nS. R. Stewart Co,\nMembers Organs Cotton\nLxdksngo\nCotton, Crain, Stocks\u2014Privet# Wires.\nPrompt Attention Given All Htxsiaees\nCorrespondents: Jno. F. Clark A C*.\nRooms 4411-402 Woodward Bldg.\nPkeuet Main 567 and 93M\nWo buy and sell Liberty Bonds.\nI*\u201d\nHubbard Bros. Co.\nfork. Members New York Cotton Exchangt^\nMew Orleans Cotton Exchange, New Yorh j\nProduce Exchange. Associated Members Li.. I\nerpool Cotton Association. Orders solicits\nfor the purchase and sale of Cotto f anf\nCotton Seed Oil for future delivery Siecixl\nattention and ilSeral terms given for con-t\nsignment of spot cotton tor delivery. Con\nSHANNON CO\nBROKERS\nMember. N.w York am] New OrU.it.\nCotton Exchugn\nCorre. pendent.\nFott A Flats, 3a Wall St..\nN.w York City\nWE BUY STOCKS AND\nBONDS FOR CLIENTS ON\nMONTHLY PAYMENT PLAN.\n212-217 Empire Bid,.\nPkonet Main 322 and 323.\nLiberty Bond. Bougbt, Sold anu\nQuoted\nr/riFicklo FlurriOvS\nof the Market\"'\ndo not worry the inveetor\nwho buve high grade listed\netocke and bond* outright\nand hold, them for perma\nnent profit.\nTha Krtebel Plan of outright boy.\nIn\u00ab on wnwnim na7m?nM wilt\nof you a iom InvcNor. It\nm you to control five dine. ,i\na block of Mcurtoa. a. |on\nlarea a block of wcuriiiei a.\ncould oontral on a caab bad.\neat all dividend, while paying.\nOur magarine. \u201cInveRmen:,\nyou pom, i\n-111\n\u2014v you powad on the vital new.\nabout the better dam of lined tecuri\ndea. Ark u. to .end it to you free\nfor da month.. Dept. 1.\nMUST FEED POLES\nThis Is Only Hope of Saving Children\nThis Winter\nBy Associated Press\nLondon, October 23.\u2014One of the\naftermaths of.the Pouish-soviet war is\nthat Americans will be called upon to\nfeed and clothe more than 1,250,000 Pol\nish children this winter through the\nAmerican relief administration. Up to\nthe time of the latest outbreak of hos\ntilities, destitution had been so reduced\nthat the relief administration officials\nbelieved that Poland, with the organi\nzation the Americans had perfected,\nwould be able to carry on the work\nafter this autumn. That is considered\nimpossible now and preparations are\nunder way* for caring for as many chil\ndren as during the dark day's of last\nwinter.\nThis decision came after receipt in\nI\u00bbndon of reports of a complete sur\nvey of the country begun immediately\nafter the bolsheviki were driven hack.\nTrained observers report that the Poles\nthemselves have not painted the picture\nblack enough. After two armies had\nfought over the ground there was lit\ntle left for the children, they report.\naVid each requested immediate shipment\nof food and clothing. As far as possi\nble, distributing agents of the admin\nistration are complying with these re\nquests.\nThe organizatio nby which about $19,\n000,000 worth of food and clothing was\ndistributed in Poland in 16 months at\na cost of approximately $80,000, is vir\ntually Intact. It includes between 15,\n000 and 18,000 Poles, whose services are\npaid for by Polan\u00a3, but who worked\nunder the directiqin of a few American\nadministrative officers. The Poles also\npay for transportation from the ships,\nwarehousing and distribution. In addi\ntion they supply all flour received by\nthem through a $200,000 credit granted\nthem byr the Grain corporation.\nAlthough the distribution organiza\ntion was considerably disarranged dur\ning the recent fighting, officials here\nsay they can get into working OTder\nagain very quickly after railroad re\npairs have been completed.\nRADICALISM DAMPENED\nPoles\u2019 Experiences With Bolsheviki\nMakes Them More Conservative\nBy AnotiiM mu\nWashington, November 14.\u2014Roman Ry\nborski, Polish vice minister of finance.\nwho is in the*United States on aa oi\ncial mission, in a statement today, e.\nexperience the Polish workmen a\nsoldiers with the Russian bolsheviki h\nmade them more conservative and h\nwi]>ed out much radicalism in Poland.\nThe condition of the bolsheviki wh\nthe Poles met in battle during the\nvasion by the soviet forces, their la\nof food and clothing and their lack\nrespect for the commonest decencies m\nlife. Mr. Rvborski said, destroyed ail\nwork of the bolshevik agitators uT\npropaganda that had been expended\nprovoke a revolution in Poland.\nMr. Ryborski said his mission in l*\nUnited States was threefold: to float*\nnew Polish loan among the Poles\nAmerica, to perfect a system of sendi,\nmoney safely from the United ctates\nPoland by Polish immigrants, and to 1\nform American capital of conditions 1\nhis country.\nThe amount of the new loan, t J\nfinance minister said, has not been c\ntermined, but it would be secured\nshort-term Polish bonds, probably fiv\nyear bonds, and be payable in Poli\nmarks.\nELIHU S. COLBERT\nPUBLIC ACCOUNTANT\nFIRST NATIONAL BANK\nBUILDING\nBIRMINGHAM, ALA.\nPHONE MAIN 391\nAUDITS\u2014SYSTEMS\u2014COSTS\nUmJ. By\nNATIONAL\nBLANK BOOK\nCOMPANY\nHolyoke, Mat*.\nW^VERY type of Bound Book and\nLoose Leaf Device is made by die\nNational Blank Book Co. These\nproducts are Eagle marked so that you\ncan be sure of getting g